# Tam al'Thor · the blademaster who found the Dragon on the mountain

To the Two Rivers, Tam al'Thor is a farmer like any other, working the land and raising his son. But that plain life is a quiet shell over a harder past: he was once a blademaster and a soldier of Illian, a man who carried a heron-marked sword before he ever carried a plow. The mark of the heron and the fevered words that escape him in illness are the first clues Rand has that his birth is not what he believed.

After a battle on the slopes of Dragonmount, Tam found an infant abandoned among the cold and carried him home, raising the child as his own son. In doing so he became father to the Dragon, though for years neither he nor the world knew it. The truth of that finding sits at the root of Rand's earliest searching for who and what he truly is.

Steady and loving, Tam is the moral ground the Dragon keeps returning to — the human anchor beneath a destiny that would otherwise have no floor. His nature of emergence is natural: he is not the Power, nor the Pattern, nor prophecy, but one of the embodied, worldly people, a man of blade and soil whose ordinary fatherhood becomes one of the saga's quiet load-bearing pillars.
